---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import ExampleBlock from "../../components/ExampleBlock.astro";
import paulisumGhz from "../../../examples/paulisum_ghz.py?raw";
import tableauGhz from "../../../examples/tableau_ghz.py?raw";
import stimSampling from "../../../examples/stim_sampling.py?raw";
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, "");
const toc = [
  { label: "§ 1 Install", href: "#install" },
  { label: "§ 2 Run a Stim circuit", href: "#stim" },
  { label: "§ 3 Use the generalized tableau", href: "#tableau" },
  { label: "§ 4 Pauli propagation", href: "#paulisum" },
  { label: "§ 5 Next steps", href: "#next" },
];
---
<Base title="Python Quick Start" current="quickstart" toc={toc}>
  <div class="qs-hero qs-hero--python">
    <div class="qs-hero-inner">
      <span class="chip"><span class="chip-dot"></span>Python · For researchers</span>
      <h1><span class="lang">py</span>Quick Start</h1>
      <p class="audience">
        For physicists and students who want to <strong>run circuits under noise</strong>
        and inspect outcomes — without writing any Rust. Code you'd paste into a
        Jupyter cell.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <article class="shell narrow qs-page qs-page--python">
    <h2 id="install"><span class="sec-num">§ 1</span>Install</h2>

    <p>
      Requires Python ≥ 3.10. The native extension is compiled automatically
      from Rust during install. We recommend using
      <a href="https://docs.astral.sh/uv/">uv</a> to manage your Python environment.
    </p>

<pre><code>uv add git+https://github.com/QuEraComputing/ppvm.git#subdirectory=ppvm-python</code></pre>

    <h2 id="stim"><span class="sec-num">§ 2</span>Run a Stim circuit, sample shots</h2>

    <p>
      The most common entry point for a researcher: parse a Stim program,
      sample it many times, and look at the empirical distribution of
      measurement outcomes. The snippet below prepares a GHZ-2 state and
      tallies the (q₀, q₁) outcomes over 200 shots.
    </p>

    <ExampleBlock code={stimSampling} file="docs/examples/stim_sampling.py" />

    <p>
      Every shot is a list of <code>MeasurementResult</code> values:
      <code>ZERO</code>, <code>ONE</code>, or <code>LOST</code> when an atom
      has been lost. Loss is first-class, so you can model neutral-atom
      hardware effects without leaving the Stim flow.
    </p>

    <h2 id="tableau"><span class="sec-num">§ 3</span>Use the generalized tableau directly</h2>

    <p>
      When you'd rather build the circuit gate-by-gate in Python — or when
      you need non-Clifford gates the Stim grammar can't express — drive a
      <code>GeneralizedTableau</code> directly:
    </p>

    <ExampleBlock code={tableauGhz} file="docs/examples/tableau_ghz.py" />

    <p>
      The tableau exposes single- and two-qubit Clifford gates, T and rotation
      gates for non-Clifford steps, projective Z-basis measurements, and
      depolarizing / loss / Pauli-error noise channels. See the
      <a href={`${base}/api#python-section`}>Python API reference</a> for the full
      list.
    </p>

    <h2 id="paulisum"><span class="sec-num">§ 4</span>Compute expectation values with Pauli propagation</h2>

    <p>
      For observable-centric studies — “what is the expectation value of this
      operator after this circuit?” — use <code>PauliSum</code> and propagate
      backwards in the Heisenberg picture:
    </p>

    <ExampleBlock code={paulisumGhz} file="docs/examples/paulisum_ghz.py" />

    <p>
      Pauli propagation scales well when the observable has small support and
      the circuit doesn't grow that support too quickly. Truncation strategies
      (<code>CoefficientThreshold</code>, <code>MaxPauliWeight</code>,
      <code>MaxLossWeight</code>, <code>CombinedStrategy</code>) let you bound
      the working set on the fly.
    </p>

    <h2 id="next"><span class="sec-num">§ 5</span>Next steps</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Browse the full <a href={`${base}/api#python-section`}>Python API reference</a>.</li>
      <li>Read the <a href="https://github.com/QuEraComputing/bloqade">Bloqade SDK</a> docs to see how ppvm fits into circuit authoring and dispatch.</li>
      <li>If you start customizing low-level behaviour or want to embed ppvm in another tool, jump to the <a href={`${base}/quickstart/rust`}>Rust Quick Start</a>.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="qs-crosslink">
      <div>
        <span class="label">Other path</span>
        Building a library on top of ppvm?
      </div>
      <a href={`${base}/quickstart/rust`}>Open the Rust Quick Start</a>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
